flowRoot.flowPara: Haskell has a concise, clean syntax and pure functional semantics. Its strong static type system infers what you mean, so you don't have to write out types if you don't want to. Pure code reads in a declarative way, with pattern matching removing boilerplate deconstruction code.
Utrecht Summerschool on Applied Functional Programming
Well-Typed's introductory and advanced Haskell courses
where sieve (p:xs) = p : sieve [x | x <- xs, x `mod` p /= 0]
